# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baptist-union-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] The **Confession of Faith (1689)**, also known as the **1689 Baptist Confession of Faith**, or the **Second London Confession of Faith (2LCF)**, is a Particular Baptist confession of faith.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] It was written by English Baptists who subscribed to a Calvinistic soteriology as well as to a non-Westminsterian covenantal systematic theology.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] Because it was revised by the Philadelphia Baptist Association in the 18th century, it is also known as the **Philadelphia Confession of Faith**.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] The Philadelphia Confession, however, was a modification of the Second London Confession; it added an allowance for the singing of hymns, psalms, and spiritual songs in the Lord's Supper and made optional the laying on of hands after baptism (Confirmation).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] The Second London Confession of Faith was first published in London in 1677 under the title "A confession of Faith put forth by the Elders and Brethren of many Congregations of Christians, Baptized upon Profession of their Faith in London and the Country.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] With an Appendix concerning Baptism." It was a revision of the Savoy Declaration (1658) with modifications to reflect Baptist theology.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] *Savoy* is itself a Congregationalist revision of the Westminster Confession (1646).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] The Confession was published again, under the same title, in 1688 and 1689.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] The Act of Toleration passed by the Parliament of England in 1689 enabled religious freedom and plurality to co-exist alongside the established churches in England and Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] In response to the Act, representatives from over 100 Baptist churches assembled in the City of London from 3–12 September of 1689 to discuss and endorse the 1677 document.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] The Confession consists of 32 chapters, as well as an introduction and a list of signatories.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] Baptists were quick to develop churches in colonial America, and in 1707 the Philadelphia Baptist Association was formed.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] The Association formally adopted a revision of the 1689 Confession in 1742 after years of tacit endorsement by local churches and congregational members.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] With the addition of two articles (on the singing of psalms and the laying on of hands), it was entitled the *Philadelphia Confession of Faith*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] Baptist churches around the world continue to subscribe to the 1689 Second London Confession of Faith as the fullest statement of their beliefs.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] Many of these churches are listed in directories like the Reformed Wiki, the Farese Church Directory and the 1689 Church Directory.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] Efforts have been made in recent years to modernize the language of the 1689 Baptist Confession to make it more accessible to contemporary readers.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] Some approaches are rather free, such as SM Houghton's *A Faith to Confess,* while others, such as Jeremy Walker's *Rooted and Grounded,* are more conservative*.* Still others, like Stan Reeve's *The 1689 Baptist Confession of Faith In Modern English* lie somewhere between.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/1689-baptist-confession-of-faith] Several expositions of the Confession have been published in recent years.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS was the successor to the former Scottish Council of Churches.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It was one of the four national ecumenical bodies in the UK, with equivalent bodies being Churches Together in England, Cytûn in Wales and the Irish Council of Churches, plus Churches Together in Britain and Ireland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The ACTS office was originally located in Dunblane, then in Alloa and finally in Stirling.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2019, the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland announced that ACTS would be succeeded by a new body to be called the Scottish Christian Forum.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2021 it was decided not to establish the SCF as a charity.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2024 the Scottish Christian Forum was recognised by Scottish churches as the main ecumenical organisation for Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It is an umbrella term for the Ecumenical Officers Forum and the Scottish Church Leaders' Forum.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS continues in existence as a charity, its principle activity being to provide grant aid to new local or national ecumenical initiatives in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] From May 2018, the interim general secretary was the Rev.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Ian Boa (who succeeded the Reverend Matthew Ross, a minister of the Church of Scotland, who took up a new post with the World Council of Churches).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The assistant general secretary (since 2011) was the Reverend Ian Boa of the United Free Church of Scotland; he succeeded the Revd Lindsey Sanderson of the United Reformed Church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] There were also two programme officers to support the work of ACTS.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] When first created, the office of ACTS was located at the former *Scottish Churches House* in Dunblane.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] In 2006 the ACTS office was moved to Forrester Lodge, adjacent to Inglewood House in Alloa, but in October 2015 it was relocated to Stirling, in a self-contained office within the headquarters building of *Volunteer Scotland*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Scottish Churches House was opened in 1960, closed in 2011 and subsequently converted into a hotel.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS was a place for churches to meet, experience, reflect, share and act together.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] There were a number of projects which ACTS coordinates across Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It was not intended that ACTS should develop into a "superchurch".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Prior to 2003, four member churches of ACTS were part of the "Scottish Churches Initiative for Union" (which sought institutional unity - a project which ACTS was not part of), but a negative vote at the General Assembly in 2003 necessitated the withdrawal of the Church of Scotland from SCIFU.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Henceforth, greater emphasis has been placed on the development of Local Ecumenical Partnerships.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The principle of being Churches Together was of central importance to the work of ACTS.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The agenda of ACTS was set at a national level by the church denominations through their representatives on the "Members' Meeting".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] To comply with the requirements of the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator, the legal responsibility for the oversight and governance of ACTS is vested in trustees, chaired by the convener of ACTS and supported by the Secretariat.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] As of 2025 the board of trustees remains in existence.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] ACTS worked through its Programme Groups, Partner Group and Bodies in Association.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Programme Groups (directly under the responsibility of ACTS) include the Scottish Churches Rural Group, Scottish Churches Anti-Human Trafficking Group and the Scottish Churches Education Group.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Partner Groups (administratively and financially supported by ACTS, but with autonomous management) include the Scottish Churches Racial Justice Group.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The ACTS Ecumenical Development Group promoted local ecumenism.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Before restructuring in the early 2010s, ACTS had four "Networks".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] A separate body, the Scottish Churches' Committee, is responsible for liaison with public authorities on legal (rather than spiritual) matters - such as changes to legislation and the resulting effect on churches (such as planning law, changes to local government taxation, etc.).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] Seven of the nine members of ACTS are also members of the SCC (i.e. all but the two smallest, namely the Congregational Federation and the Quakers).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The SCC also includes the Baptist Church, the Free Church of Scotland and several smaller Presbyterian churches.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] The Secretary of the SCC is the Solicitor of the Church of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/action-of-churches-together-in-scotland] It also co-operates with the UK-wide Churches Legislation Advisory Services (CLAS), formerly known as the Churches' Main Committee.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Reverend James Paterson DD, the first pastor, started the church in a rented room on North Portland Street, Glasgow in 1829.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Due to the growth of the congregation, the church moved to a large hall in Inkle Factory Lane, and then in 1835 to a church building they had commissioned on Hope Street, Glasgow.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The Hope Street building is now part of Glasgow Central Station.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The church then commissioned a new building on Adelaide Place (now part of Bath Street) in the 1870s.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The congregation moved into the new building in 1876.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Another branch of the church was established in the early 1880s on St Clair Street, Maryhill.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] While still in Hope Street, the church provided evening classes in elementary education.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] These classes were gradually phased out with the introduction of a compulsory public education system in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Paterson was one of the founders of the Glasgow Commercial College in 1846.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The college aimed to provide a university-level commercial education to young businessmen.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Paterson himself taught Logic and Rhetoric and the college also taught Political Economy and other subjects.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] It met in the Anderson Buildings on George Street, Glasgow.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The college later merged with the Glasgow Athenaeum, which was the ancestor of the University of Strathclyde.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The Baptist Theological College was founded in 1894, and until 1925 it was housed within Adelaide Place Baptist Church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The first president was Professor Joseph Coats MD who was a deacon of Adelaide Place for many years.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Three early pastors of the church also served as tutors at the college: Dr.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] More recently, Jack Quinn (pastor from 1984 to 2013) tutored at the college.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] In 1870, the Baptist Union of Scotland was formed of 51 churches in the hall of Hope Street Chapel (which later moved to Adelaide Place).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Howard Bowser, a former deacon and treasurer of Hope Street Chapel, became president of the Baptist Union in 1871 and the philanthropist Thomas Coats (1809–1883) took over the presidency in 1873.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Adelaide Place was for many years the centre of denomination activity for Baptists in Scotland, with the annual Baptist Assembly often being held on the premises.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Twenty men from Adelaide Place and a further 17 from the St.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Clair Street branch (near Maryhill Road) were killed in the First World War.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Six men from Adelaide Place were killed in the Second World War.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The names of the fallen from both wars are inscribed on a commemorative communion table.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The St Clair Street Women's Fellowship started two sewing meetings to make up comfort packages for church members on active service.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Some female members of the congregation volunteered to help with air raid precautions, and Marjorie McInnes regularly carried out fire-watch duties from the church roof during blackout.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] During the war, the main church building was open to the public every day for meditation and prayer.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The BBC broadcast to the Empire a radio programme of a church service held in Adelaide Place on 9 March 1941.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] In 1933, £2,500 was raised to carry out repairs to the stonework of the church, which had been damaged by smoke pollution, and to make improvements to the St Clair Street Halls, the manse and the Church Officer's house.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] St Clair Street Women's Fellowship had been set up at the St Clair Street location as a response to female hardship during the years of the Great Depression.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] It continued until 1952, when the project was closed and the St Clair Street building sold, due to the reduced population of Glasgow city centre as people moved out to the new suburbs.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The depopulation of the city centre placed pressure upon the church, as a smaller congregation struggled with the costs of the church building and activities.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] In the 1950s and 1960s the church discussed the possibility of merging with another city centre church or moving out of the city centre, but decided against both options.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] In the 1970s, the church set up the Adelaide Place Baptist Church Development Trust to coordinate a renovation project.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The stonework was cleaned, a new heating system was installed, carpet was laid and the church was rewired.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Donald McCallum was so moved by a meeting with a homeless woman that, with some volunteers, he opened a flat to house and care for vulnerable young women in the vicinity of the church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] In 1982, a charitable trust was set up to run the initiative.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] McCallum named it the Elpis Centre after the Greek word for 'hope'.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The Elpis Centre now offers accommodation and support to around 18 vulnerable women at any one time.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Dry rot was discovered in the building in the early 1990s.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Once again, there were discussions about closing the building and moving the congregation to the suburbs because of the expense of repairs.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The congregation instead decided on extensive renovation and redevelopment programme, incorporating businesses that could feed their profits back into the work of the church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Adelaide Place Development Company Ltd (SC142177), with the trading name 'Adelaides', was set up in 1993 to oversee the business, and work commenced in 1994.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The eastern part of the church was converted into a guest house, the basement into a nursery, and a mezzanine cafe was set up with access from Bath Street.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The main auditorium was also made available for hire at times when it was not being used by the congregation.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The cafe was later closed, with the facilities being used by the guest house and nursery instead.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The church carried out another renovation project, named 'The Light of Renewal', in 2017- 2023.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The building's external stonework was repaired in 2017.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The guest house was closed in 2018 and the bedrooms and reception office were converted back to offices and meeting rooms for the church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The audiovisual system was also updated in 2018.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The main auditorium was renovated in 2022 - 2023, with the installation of a community cafe space, re-glazing of the windows and improvements to disabled access.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Adelaide Place Baptist Church was built between 1875 and 1877 and was designed by Thomas Lennox Watson.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Its entrances are at 209 Bath Street and 188 Pitt Street, Glasgow.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] At the Pitt Street entrance, a stone staircase leads up to three double doors, while the Bath Street entrance has street-level access.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The church is built in the neo-classical Italianate style from polished blonde ashlar stone.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] It has a raised temple front on Pitt Street, with Corinthian columns supporting a pediment, three recessed doorways with panelled outer doors and glass inner doors.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The front is flanked by pedimented blocks on either side.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] There are sash and case windows and arcaded windows with outer pilasters on both elevations (Bath Street and Bath Lane).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The auditorium has a balcony at the back and both sides of the space, supported by pillars.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] At the front of the auditorium there is a platform with access ramp and steps, flanked by columns and topped with a rounded pediment.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] There was previously a baptistery under the stage but this was removed during refurbishment in 2022.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Many of the pipes of the former pipe organ, set in dark wood, are still present behind the platform.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] There are three stained glass windows by W. and J.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Kerr in the west wall, above the balcony.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] They show Christ and the Wise Virgins; Timothy and his Mother; Paul and Isaiah.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Christ and the Wise Virgins was dedicated by James Wilson, Provost of Govan, in memory of his sister-in-law Victoria Graham Taylor who died in 1873 at the age of 19.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Timothy and his Mother was dedicated by one Herman Bowser in memory of his wife and son.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] President of the Scottish Temperance League and editor of the Scottish Temperance Journal.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Quarrier was a philanthropist who founded Orphan Homes of Scotland, which later became the charity Quarriers.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Coats was a deacon of the church and also the first president of the Baptist Theological College.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] A member of APBC for almost 50 years, serving as a deacon, senior trustee and treasurer.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The only woman ever to be elected President of the Baptist Union of Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] As a contributor to the Cope Report, she was jointly responsible for the establishment of social work as a profession in Scotland.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] As the membership of Adelaide Place Baptist Church increased, groups of members sometimes founded new congregations in areas of Glasgow with large or growing populations that did not yet have a Baptist church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] In 1845 a church was formed in Blackfriars Street (later called John Knox Street) by members of the Hope Street Hall (later Adelaide Place Baptist Church).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The building was designed by Thomas Lennox Watson, who also designed the Adelaide Place building.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] John Knox Street Baptist Church was demolished in 1965.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The congregation of **Queens Park Baptist Church** was formed in 1878 by four members of Adelaide Place Baptist Church, to serve the needs of the growing suburb of Queens Park on Glasgow's south side.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] This church decided to commission the present church building in 1884 and moved into the new premises in 1887.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Members from Hillhead Baptist Church and Adelaide Place Baptist Church started meeting in Bearsden in 1973.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The congregation became **Bearsden Baptist Church**, which first called a minister in 1975.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Queens Park Baptist Church, Bearsden Baptist Church and Hillhead Baptist Church are still in operation, although the original Hillhead church building is being converted to flats.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Partick Baptist Church is now a campus of Queens Park Baptist Church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] The rest of the work of the church is carried out by eight teams of volunteers, each team serving a different function.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Children's work in the church takes place during the service, led by volunteers from the APBC Kids team.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adelaide-place-baptist-church] Adelaide Place Baptist Church is a registered Scottish charity (charity number SC013073) and members of the Core Leadership Team are also trustees of the charity.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Seventh-day Adventists and some smaller Adventist groups observe the seventh day Sabbath.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The General Conference of Seventh-day Adventists has compiled that church's core beliefs in the 28 Fundamental Beliefs (1980 and 2005).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] In 2010, Adventism claimed to have some 22 million believers who were scattered in various independent churches.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The largest church within the movement—the Seventh-day Adventist Church—had more than 23 million members in 2025.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Adventism began as an inter-denominational movement.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Its most vocal leader was William Miller.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Between 50,000 and 100,000 people in the United States supported Miller's predictions of Christ's return.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] After the "Great Disappointment" of October 22, 1844, many people in the movement gave up on Adventism.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Of those remaining Adventist, the majority gave up believing in any prophetic (biblical) significance for the October 22 date, yet they remained expectant of the near Advent (second coming of Jesus).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Of those who retained the October 22 date, many maintained that Jesus had come not literally but "spiritually", and consequently were known as "spiritualizers".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] A small minority held that something concrete had indeed happened on October 22, but that this event had been misinterpreted.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] This belief later emerged and crystallized with the Seventh-day Adventist Church, the largest remaining body.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Albany Conference in 1845, attended by 61 delegates, was called to attempt to determine the future course and meaning of the Millerite movement.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Following this meeting, the "Millerites" then became known as "Adventists" or "Second Adventists".
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] However, the delegates disagreed on several theological points.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Four groups emerged from the conference: The Evangelical Adventists, The Life and Advent Union, the Advent Christian Church, and the Seventh-day Adventist Church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The largest group was organized as the American Millennial Association, a portion of which was later known as the Evangelical Adventist Church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Unique among the Adventists, they believed in an eternal hell and consciousness in death.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] They declined in numbers, and by 1916 their name did not appear in the United States Census of Religious Bodies.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It has diminished to almost non-existence today.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Their main publication was the *Advent Herald*, of which Sylvester Bliss was the editor until his death in 1863.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It was later called the *Messiah's Herald*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Life and Advent Union was founded by George Storrs in 1863.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] He had established *The Bible Examiner* in 1842.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It merged with the Adventist Christian Church in 1964.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Advent Christian Church officially formed in 1861 and grew rapidly at first.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It declined a little during the 20th century.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Advent Christians publish the four magazines *The Advent Christian Witness*, *Advent Christian News*, *Advent Christian Missions* and *Maranatha*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] They also operate a liberal arts college at Aurora, Illinois; and a one-year Bible College in Lenox, Massachusetts, called Berkshire Institute for Christian Studies.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Primitive Advent Christian Church later separated from a few congregations in West Virginia.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Seventh-day Adventist Church officially formed in 1863.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It believes in the sanctity of the seventh-day Sabbath as a holy day for worship.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It publishes the *Adventist Review*, which evolved from several early church publications.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Youth publications include *KidsView*, *Guide* and *Insight*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It has grown to a large worldwide denomination and has a significant network of medical and educational institutions.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Miller did not join any of the movements, and he spent the last few years of his life working for unity, before dying in 1849.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Christadelphians were founded in 1844 by John Thomas.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] In 2000, there were an estimated 25,000 members in 170 ecclesias, or churches, in the United States.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **Advent Christian Church** was founded in 1860 and had 25,277 members in 302 churches in 2002 in America.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It is a "first-day" body of Adventist Christians founded on the teachings of William Miller.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It adopted the "conditional immortality" doctrine of Charles F.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Hudson and George Storrs, who formed the "Advent Christian Association" in Salem, Massachusetts, in 1860.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **Primitive Advent Christian Church** is a small group which separated from the Advent Christian Church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It differs from the parent body mainly on two points.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Its members observe foot washing as a rite of the church, and they teach that reclaimed backsliders should be baptized (even though they had formerly been baptized).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] This is sometimes referred to as rebaptism.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **Seventh-day Adventist Church**, founded in 1863, had over 23,000,000 baptized members (not counting children of members) worldwide in 2025.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It is best known for its teaching that Saturday, the seventh day of the week, is the Sabbath and is the appropriate day for worship.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] However, the second coming of Jesus Christ, along with Judgment Day based on the three angels' message in Revelation 14:6–13, remain core beliefs of Seventh-day Adventists.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **Seventh Day Adventist Reform Movement** is a small offshoot with an unknown number of members from the Seventh-day Adventist Church caused by disagreement over military service on the Sabbath day during World War I.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **Davidians** (originally named **Shepherd's Rod**) is a small offshoot with an unknown number of members made up primarily of voluntarily disfellowshipped members of the Seventh-day Adventist Church.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] They were originally known as the Shepherd's Rod and are still sometimes referred to as such.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The group derives its name from two books on Bible doctrine written by its founder, Victor Houteff, in 1929.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Branch Davidians were a split ("branch") from the Davidians.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] A group that gathered around David Koresh (the so-called *Koreshians*) abandoned Davidian teachings and turned into a religious cult.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Many of them were killed during the infamous Waco Siege of April 1993.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **Church of God (Seventh-Day)** was founded in 1863 and it had an estimated 11,000 members in 185 churches in 1999 in America.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Its founding members separated in 1858 from those Adventists associated with Ellen G.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] White who later organized themselves as Seventh-day Adventists in 1863.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Church of God (Seventh Day) split in 1933, creating two bodies: one headquartered in Salem, West Virginia, and known as the Church of God (7th day) – Salem Conference and the other one headquartered in Denver, Colorado and known as the General Conference of the Church of God (Seventh-Day).
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The Worldwide Church of God splintered from this.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Many denominations known as "Church of God" have Adventist origins.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **Church of God General Conference** was founded in 1921 and had 7,634 members in 162 churches in 2004 in America.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] It is a nontrinitarian first-day Adventist Christian body which is also known as the *Church of God of the Abrahamic Faith* and the *Church of God General Conference (Morrow, GA)*.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **Creation Seventh-Day Adventist Church** is a small group that broke off from the Seventh-Day Adventists in 1988, and organized itself as a church in 1991.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The **United Seventh-Day Brethren** is a small Sabbatarian Adventist body.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] In 1947, several individuals and two independent congregations within the Church of God Adventist movement formed the *United Seventh-Day Brethren*, seeking to increase fellowship and to combine their efforts in evangelism, publications, and other .
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Early in its development, the Bible Student movement founded by Charles Taze Russell had close connections with the Millerite movement and stalwarts of the Adventist faith, including George Storrs and Joseph Seiss.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] The various independent Bible Student groups currently have a cumulative membership of about 20,000 worldwide.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] According to the Watch Tower Society, there were about 9 million Jehovah's Witnesses worldwide as of 2025.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/adventist] Adventist churches only support marriage between one man and one woman.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Baptists later emerged in the 18th century—in 1750 at Keiss, where the leader was William Sinclair and the church was established on the English Baptist pattern.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] The group who in Edinburgh came to Baptist convictions in 1765 under the leadership of Robert Carmichael and Archibald McLean became known as **Scotch Baptists**.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Like other Scottish Protestant Christians of the time they were very conservative and adopted the opinions of a particularly strict form of Calvinism.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Somewhat later, a different form of Baptist witness emerged, this time influenced by the Haldane brothers, James Haldane and Robert Haldane evangelical preachers who came to Baptist convictions around 1808.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Along with the *English Baptists*, they were distinguished from the Scotch Baptists by their more moderate and less Calvinistic attitudes.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] After overcoming initial hostilities, all these groups were able to unite in 1869.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] The Baptist Union of Scotland was founded in Hope Street Chapel in Glasgow (later Adelaide Place Baptist Church) in 1869, with 51 churches in its membership, which represented almost 4000 members.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] One of its early presidents (in 1873) was the philanthropist Thomas Coats.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Following on from the Covid Pandemic, the denomination strived to make 'increasing their membership in all 150 churches' their core vision through three strategic priorities of congregations and the denomination: prayer, church planting, and leaders' training.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] In 2019, the congregation had 10,600 members and 158 churches.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] According to a census published by the association in 2023, it claimed 9,946 members and 156 churches.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] As of March 2025, the denomination had 9,452 members and 153 churches.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] The Baptist Union of Scotland is served by a National team comprising: Rev Dr Martin Hodson (General Director), Rev.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Lisa Holmes (Deeper Church Lead), Mr Brian Windram (Finance Director), Ms.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Lyndsay Cameron-Ross (Communications Lead) Rev Ali Laing (Younger Generation & Digital Church Lead), Rev Professor Andrew Clarke (Leadership Development Lead) and Rev.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] In 2022/2023, the denomination reported a growth in membership, of 1%, for the first time in 40 years.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] During 2023 and 2024, they were seeing about baptisms across their churches each year than they had in the years before the Covid pandemic.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Their hope and prayer is to see 40 new Baptist churches revitalised or planted by 2030.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] Initial work has begun in Denny, Dundee and Newton Mearns.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] The Convention has a Baptist confession of faith.
[src:baptist-union-of-scotland/baptist-union-of-scotland] It is a member of the Baptist World Alliance.
